A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of every car.
The devices that record every mile driven and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning offices to revise the outdated system for financing U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have teamed up with environmental groups and are calling for the government to use the small boxes to record the kilometers traveled – and possibly where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax returns.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a move, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how to switch to a system where drivers pay per mile driven over the next ten years.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the dials, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s not something we’ll just possibly use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record the miles driven by all California drivers in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, funded from the taxes Americans pay at the pinnacle, is bankrupt.
In America, however, there is no longer as much gasoline as before.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per liter) has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by a penny at high alcohol prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transport law expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state has recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mileage-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful alternative in the long term,” he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as a mileage-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is appealing to urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way as to reduce congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases.
The California planners are relying on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally anchored goals on climate change.
But Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, also said he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also driven by the idea of having drivers pay for a distance traveled.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transportation Ministers who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move toward miles-based billing.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would cover 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the advance, responding to the concerns of MPs from rural areas, who represent people who often have to travel many miles on the way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Nevertheless, several states and big cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most committed is Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the mineral oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City also considers one.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, drivers were skeptical of the idea that the government could track each of their movements.
“Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, Head of Strategy and Results Management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
The people didn't want it.
As the test began, the Nevada ACLU warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data about the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that will allow the state to track the kilometres traveled, but not exactly when and where.
That, Khan said, would also reassure the public.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company did not initially step in to help state governments tax drivers.
Rather, it was their goal to set foot in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers should pay based on the miles driven.
But the devices tested by her are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
“People are more likely to get involved if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programs have made major mistakes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they don’t choose a device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average mileage driven by all residents of the state.
Others hope to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more functions than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxation device that can also pay parking fees, only have to pay insurance for kilometers driven, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which drivers can avoid congestion.
“Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the system,” the city’s planning document states.
However, some traffic planners wonder if the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or annual levy could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they too pay a fair share.
“There is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is enough,” said Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
