U.S. Border: "Super Tunnel" for Drug Smuggling Discovered
At the border between Mexico and the United States, investigators have discovered and shut down a "super tunnel" for drug smuggling.
According to U.S. customs officials, the more than 500-metre-long tube between Tijuana and San Diego was equipped with electricity, railroads and a ventilation system.
Three suspects were arrested and eight tons of marijuana and nearly 150 kilograms of cocaine confiscated.
The tunnel was reportedly not in use yet.
“These cartels are stupid if they think they could dig under the radar,” U.S. District Attorney General Laura Duffy said at a press conference outside a warehouse in San Diego, where one end of the tunnel had been discovered.
“If you continue to build such tunnels and try to use them, we are determined to make this a huge waste of your dirty money,” Duffy said.
Both the U.S. authorities and the Mexican security forces are in an ongoing fight against the drug cartel.
Since 2006, more than 77,000 people have been killed in connection with drug crime in Mexico.
Designed by experts
Due to the complex equipment of the tunnel, the investigators assume that it was designed by architects and engineers and that the construction took about a year.
The rail system was equipped in such a way that electric vehicles could be used there.
On the Mexican side, the access is in a building that is 80 meters from the border.
According to authorities, a ladder leads 20 meters deep to the actual tunnel entrance.
The tunnel has a cross section of 1.20 meters high and 90 centimeters wide.
It would also have been suitable to encourage illegal immigration to the United States.
Two of the suspects were arrested in connection with the cocaine discovery.
The third, a Mexican, was arrested for the seizure of marijuana.
All three are threatened with life imprisonment, officials said.
Since 2006, eight such tunnels have been discovered, it was further stated at the press conference in San Diego.
This is the first time cocaine has been found in such a tunnel.
Normally, cocaine is smuggled in smaller quantities and not through tunnels.
