ESA decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Faraway planets, gravitational waves or black holes – experts at the European Space Agency now have to agree on two major projects they want to launch in the coming years.
There were 30 proposals to choose from, five are still in the race.
Far away worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been discovered by astronomers.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should we look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origins of the cosmos?
Or looking for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering extraterrestrial life?
These questions are being asked by those responsible for the European Space Agency ESA.
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are crucial to advance research.
The state for such "L-missions" is approximately one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the European space exploration elite met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were debated, five of which have now come to the narrower choice.
Numerous panels reviewed the proposals and followed up with the researchers.
In the coming days, a final decision will be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee.
In total, ESA has selected four major questions to be answered by the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme launched in 2007.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets that orbit these stars - are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has a planet, under what circumstances can life arise there?
To answer this question, the Cheops Space Telescope is expected to launch in 2017 to investigate 500 known planetary systems in our immediate surroundings.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
Using larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, looking for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an indicator of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately intended to give an insight into what conditions exist for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the emanating particle radiation with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be studied exemplary.
With the "Solar Orbiter" the ESA has already approved a mission of the M-Class (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is expected to launch in 2017 and closely observe the surface and activity of the sun.
Of great interest to the researchers are also Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the ESA envisages the first of a total of three L-missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) begins its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is to explore the planet's atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europa, Kallisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus examine whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
There may also be deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory under whose roof all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to our common matter, which consists of stars, planets, and living beings like us, there is dark matter whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and dark energy whose action accelerates the expansion of the universe.
So far, researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of seconds of the Big Bang, nor what Dark Matter and Dark Energy consist of.
With "Euclid", the ESA has already approved an M-mission, the start of which is planned for 2020.
Using a special telescope, the probe will investigate the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus allowing conclusions about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, the best chances of obtaining an authorisation as an L-mission is "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
This includes changes in the structure of spacetime that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, hope the scientists behind the project.
The mission includes a detector consisting of two or three probes stationed in space.
Unlike plants on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves created by the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is to explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, "finding" and "exploring" the cosmic background radiation.
Proposals for the return of samples from Mars, for the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids and for solar physics have already been eliminated.
