Frontier Airlines charges for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to demand up to $100 from passengers who want to store hand luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for a piece of hand luggage and $2 for coffee or lemonade, although the announcement on Wednesday read that passengers are allowed to keep the entire can.
The new fee applies to hand luggage in the luggage compartment above the seat, small pockets under the seat are still free.
Frontier said it would charge US$25 if the fee was paid in advance, and US$100 for travelers who only paid at the deck.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee aims to move travelers to take care of the payment in advance.
“We don’t want to calculate that amount,” she explained.
In 2008, airlines began charging fees for the first and second checked baggage.
Passengers trying to bypass these have therefore put as much in hand luggage as possible, resulting in the luggage compartments above the seat being often overcrowded.
Fees are a way to get passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee wasn't really about making money.
It’s about Frontier’s most loyal customers who have made it clear that it’s becoming increasingly difficult to find room in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline’s website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger at Frontier’s flight deck may be allowed to take one piece of luggage free of charge, but the next person must pay $100 for a comparable piece of luggage.
O'Malley said Frontier's website and check-in procedures would be changed so that passengers would be informed of the fee before arriving at the airport.
Frontier’s new hand baggage charge will only come into effect in the summer, but there is no exact date yet.
Passengers often scoff at baggage surcharges and other fees, but airlines like to resort to them.
They argue that transporting baggage costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they want it.
Many on Wall Street view the new baggage charges as a sign that airlines are taking enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
Most, however, so far leave fingers off fees for hand baggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for hand baggage three years ago and later followed by Allegiant Air, also a low-cost airliner.
The only other airline with such a fee is the Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the Spirit Hand Luggage Fee would bring in $50 million annually.
Sorensen, who previously held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious about what he would expect on the flight deck if passengers were faced with the company’s unusual hand baggage charge.
“The boarding process was one of the smoothest I’ve experienced in aviation in my career,” he said.
I expected to see toothaches and handshake discussions on the flight deck.
“The plane was full,” he explained, “and the boarding was running like lubrication.”
Frontier also follows Spirit with the 2 dollars required for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company said passengers who bought lemonade or juice were allowed to keep the entire can and coffee was replenished free of charge.
Water is still free.
US Airways briefly tried to demand money for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed this seven months later after passengers complained and no other major company was pursued.
Frontiers’ step of charging for hand baggage if passengers do not buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to direct customers to their own website.
