What happens on the way to my email?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
When designing the Internet service, was e-mail technically implemented in the same way as the traditional mail?
In the design of early Internet services, communication was made possible.
As a result, the basic technical protocols have failed to provide a stable basis for sound correspondence.
Therefore, a traditional e-mail corresponds to an open postcard rather than a sealed letter.
If the user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
The e-mail program or the browser of Anna sends the e-mail to the mail server of her service provider in the first step.
For example, if you had a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run over several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content at his provider.
Will traditional emails be read along the way through the web?
Most emails are read multiple times by software robots on the go.
The sender’s provider usually checks whether the email is running a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also performed on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam email that is immediately deleted or at least sorted away in a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems like GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place contextual advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google may display relevant links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also read the emails?
The likelihood of unauthorized people reading an email is extremely low.
Theoretically, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal opportunities to intercept or take notice of e-mails.
In addition to this, there are possible illegal spying operations.
Is it possible to protect emails from co-reading?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an email can be effectively encrypted against co-reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to conceal the metadata of an email communication, so that it is not even possible to immediately recognize who has communicated with whom.
