George Kerevan: European detachment gives the Scots the choice
A new day, a new horror story of independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is required to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
This provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire secured border along the Hadrian's Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde model pointed out the potential economic benefits that would bring more freedom of travel in the rest of Europe, but this was not expected to play a role in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favorable for them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, the continued disregard for Brussels would only be a small concession in return for what you really want from the Scots.
Not really a story.
And one that has come so far in the years that it already resembles a fossil: The first time I heard the “Independence means passport controls” duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should one expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great post-war plan to unify Europe has come to a standstill.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe officially died.
Everywhere in the EU, parties gain ground that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a community currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – was able to win nearly five million votes in the September Bundestag elections and thus effectively expel the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic resistance to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis is a turning point.
Due to the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the forced jacket, into which the respective national economy is forced by holding on to the common currency, many people have considered that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are advantageous for German exporters – and German politicians would like to let that happen.
Without the possibility of depreciation of the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – driven by Berlin.
Behind the current state and monetary problems lies a deep-rooted European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives enacted by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice for electricity and quadruples for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All of the world’s payroll bills do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is drawing up, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, the political elite of France saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and raise Paris to the heights of Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and Europe has imposed its own economic policy, which the French economy is struggling with.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National just won a decisive by-election, placing the ruling socialists in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to the UK Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits to the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among white working-class French?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to go further: In the not too distant future, the growing resentment towards the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but rather it will become something like the “Europe of the (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project in the hope of getting involved with the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can choose to be a region of (the last consequence) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which also includes telling Berlin and Brussels what they can put themselves where.
I suspect Scotland could do well in a looser European union if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similarly thought countries is easier for nations in a non-federal Europe.
Otherwise, we should consider equating it with Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and has won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and undertaken) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the ensuing Tory-Lib Demworden had.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to choose independence now, only to get a policy of austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe that epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter already grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time calming down parents – usually this is not a sign that puberty is fast approaching,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, as well as body odor, appear earlier in girls.
However, there was only a slight shift in the age of menarche (the appearance of the first regular bleeding) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
“When breast development begins, it takes at least two to three years to develop menarche,” said Kaplowitz, also author of the book “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually marks the beginning of puberty, but it is considered “pregnancy” when breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth boost before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can monitor closely.
In case of faster progress, tests may be indicated by an endichronologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatment methods for delaying an early menstruation and the defense of another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to inhibition of growth and thus small body growth in adults.
Recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the child’s age, developmental speed, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and the feelings of girls, unlike being their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: Parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had ten days.
Although there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home frightened and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are causative.
Boys, like girls, come into puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported a 2001 study of girls between the ages of six and nine that establishes a link between body fat and puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white counterparts.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys grow facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend towards a full-fledged early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who blossom early need insurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than thought.
Jumbo manufacturers are arguing over seat width in the face of large orders
There has been a dispute between leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of seats in the tourist class on long-haul flights, indicating the tone for a bitter collision at the Dubai Airshow this month.
The controversy revolves around the width of seats offered to passengers on long-haul flights in the tourist class – not always those for which airlines make the most efforts, but this designated space is the key to efficiency claims on the latest aircraft from Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
Airbus this week demanded an industry standard requiring a seat width of at least 46 cm (18 inches) in the tourist class, but the U.S. arch rival Boeing says that should be decided by airlines.
The dispute comes at a time when aircraft manufacturers are competing to sell even larger versions of their two-engine long-haul aircraft, and expect record orders at the event from November 17 to 21.
How the rear of the aircraft is designed – especially whether there are rows of nine or ten seats – is crucial for the stated economic results that the new “mini-jumbo” design is expected to deliver.
Boeing claims its modernized “777X” holds 406 seats in the tourist class that are over 17 inches wide, allowing ten per row.
Airbus explains that the competing version of the A350 carried 350 people in 18-inch wide seats in the tourist class, with there being nine per row.
Aircraft giants often share technical details through advertising in the professional press.
Airbus is now appealing directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to make the race with over 100 orders.
Recently, the company presented an ad that could be the beginning of a new ad war and showed donors an image of three people squeezed together in a restaurant, with the title, “Would you accept that?”
“Boeing is proposing long-haul flights in seats that are narrower than regional turboprops,” said Airbus chief sales officer John Leahy.
In the face of changing eating habits, people get fatter, but airplane seats have not changed radically.
Between the early 1970s, when the Boeing 747 defined modern long-haul travel, and the end of the century, the weight of the male average American between the ages of 40 and 49 increased by ten percent, according to data from the U.S. Department of Health.
According to U.S. health statistics, the waist circumference of the male average American in the 21st century is 100.8 cm.
Airbus says its rival adheres to a seat concept from the 1950s when the average body circumference of the freshly-baptized “Jet Set” was narrower.
According to Airbus, studies have shown that an additional inch (2.54 cm) per seat increases sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing denies Airbus' figures on the seat dimensions and says it is not up to the manufacturers to decide how airlines are balancing airfares and facilities.
The company also explains that, according to research, the experience on the plane depends on more than the width of the seat.
“It’s really about giving airlines the flexibility to do what they think they need to do to be successful,” said Kent Craver, Boeing’s cockpit expert.
They don’t want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable.
They know their business better than anyone else.
For passengers, it is about more elbow freedom, but for manufacturers, it will increasingly be a topic that can have an impact on sales.
Behind the controversy lies a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least $700 billion at list prices in the coming decades, which could sustainably affect the export balance of the United States or Europe.
As Reuters first reported in July, the seat layout is the driving force behind the fight over the new jets.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 percent more efficiency per seat in their latest two-engine long-haul designs than the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 77-300ER.
Boeing’s statements on the results depend in part on the fact that the 777X with its ten seats per row is compared to the original nine-seat design in the 777.
The increased cost per unit is still lower than with the currently used machines with ten seats per row.
“Boeing is squeezing more seats into its aircraft to make it more competitive with our products,” said Kevin Keniston, Head of Passenger Comfort at European Airbus.
On the other hand, analysts say full cabins with ten seats per row on existing 777s indicated that many passengers opted for the tighter arrangement, which could be accompanied by cheaper airfares.
“Eighteen-inch seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is that from an economic point of view, the Airbus offer is driven by the threat from the 777,” said Mary Kirby, cabin installation expert, founder and editor of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The world-famous jet sellers even carry bandwidth with them to match the facility to the competition.
Even if they praise comfort, all manufacturers also offer jets with high-density design for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seat rows, but has not yet sold one, according to its own statement.
Until recently, Airbus has emphasized the importance of greater adaptability of the cabins and offered wide seats on the aisles for some jets.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets, experts say the reputation for a new industry standard is likely to stifle, but could distract from the wave of 777X sales.
New anti-nicotine vaccine could make the pleasure of smoking go away
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
Further tests on humans are needed, which may take a few more years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are good.
“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once again help millions of smokers who have tried to quit trying all the methods available on the market but have had to experience that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information for the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies chase the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, causing a smoker to experience no nicotine high.
In trials, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal activity levels.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken “a break,” the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Former tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so often to maintain the level of antibodies that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it transforms liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it is completely safe, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
However, it is more likely that smokers would use it to stop.
“They know that when they start smoking again, they don’t feel comfortable with the nicotine vaccine anymore, and that helps them quit the habit,” he explains.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but at the same time warned that further research was needed.
