Firming jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, mortgages in Singapore require an effective annual rate of 17 percent, which is just above the 15.4 percent required by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, mortgage houses offer the advantage that there is no need to verify creditworthiness or proof of income, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region are turning to mortgages after families feel pressured by rising living costs as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to loose financial policies in the developed economies, low- and middle-income families are looking for mortgages to make up for the difference in a stagnant economy.
This week, the credit rating agency Standard & Poor’s growing domestic debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, described it as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have, according to the agency, the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
