Economists are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
“In the end, this means that given rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical peaks in gold prices over the past two years have further strengthened the trend towards the pledge of personal items as people seize the opportunity to turn the family’s jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city-state’s 200 pledge houses are gold.
People say, “The gold price looks good, let’s pledge Grandmother’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
The largest Thai mortgage operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent customer growth in its branches in recent months.
