FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on airplanes (but do not conduct cell phone calls)
Passengers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but not phone, according to new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depends on the respective airline, FAA staff member Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals as well as the provisions for storing the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the airplane doors are closed.
They are only allowed to restart until the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
Passengers must turn it off again when they enter landing and are not allowed to restart until the plane has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even during take-off, landing and rolling, the FAA said.
Most new transport aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional flight attendants’ association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” Glading said.
We are frankly tired of having to feel like guardians on this issue.
However, internet connections for browsing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
