Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transport safety expert, told CBS News that mobile phones would still be considered a risk.
“Handys are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that airborne transmission can also interfere with transmitters,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate the issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to ease restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri are of the view that there are no valid security grounds for the ban.
Restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, it is reported that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore turning off the device.
In 1966, the FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers after reports of navigation and communication equipment malfunctions were made known by passenger-carried UHF radios, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that they do not care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years when the flight altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the stronger use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
For example, e-readers only emit minimal radiation when you flip.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Amazon.com is one of the proponents of easing restrictions on the use of devices by passengers.
