Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings regarding the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the disruption by the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports of pilots speaking out for aircraft systems to be disrupted by the devices, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the passengers to shut down the equipment when instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
