Scientists were able to shed more light on the relationship between a dog’s tail waving and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with the tail barked more to the right (from the dog’s point of view) while nervous dogs had the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive these subtle differences and react to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres of the brain respond differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to the side-tails of their peers, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-leggeds and analyzed the behavior.
We will probably soon understand why the tail moves in one direction, in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs films with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved its tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the barking dog), they remained completely relaxed.
However, if the tail tilt was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog that races), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience what movements to worry about and when not.
He said, “If you have different encounters with other dogs and waving your tail in one direction is more of a friendly behavior and the right side is more of a less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their pet’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behavior and a guest fellow at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right when looking at a satisfied dog.
Another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada stated: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robotic dog when his ‘tail’ races to the left rather than the right, rather than becoming restless – just the opposite of the Italian study.”
According to him, the differences could be that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain halves are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior can be easily recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
