My classmates wept for joy and my parents gathered all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had an approval rating of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is an evil awakening, as if you are being pulled out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague reminder, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I gave my vote for the first time, something has actually changed.
But it's just nothing I could have imagined.
I acknowledge the great and varied things Obama has accomplished, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for Health Insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced concealment of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that the party-political blockade tactics have tipped too many aspirations to advance our nation: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name just a few.
But after defending the Obama administration against colleagues and acquaintances countless times, I have come to the end with my attempts to explain.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why it is permissible to intercept foreign heads of state or to kill innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data about the privacy of Americans and why whistleblowers who reveal state misconduct are being punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits are being circumvented during the presidential election.
It does not justify the results of a report that says the White House’s efforts to calm the media are the “most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And most recently, it can’t excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the passage of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at the age of 18 that the work of government could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the MP office is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape the public discussion.
But when I look at the examples mentioned above, they seem to have largely been elected by the government itself.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I elected Obama again in 2012, not because I was thrilled with his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confusing and unbiased alternative, he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard of for so long.
But with Obama’s approval ratings dropping below 45% this week, the book’s return to 2008 has become all the more difficult.
