En route through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical care to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one in 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is in the top 10 of CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose him as "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner receives $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, Cameroon's capital, in 1981.
At first he had only a broken arm, but then an inflammation formed that spread to his brain, causing a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
“It’s not easy,” commented Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
There is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, in the United States, the ratio is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for her, most Cameroonians couldn’t afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of the country’s health spending is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
Poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
To see his father and so many of his compatriots suffering in Bwelle matured the decision to do something against it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
In addition, he founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people force themselves into minibuses and drive with their medical equipment on the roof over unfastened terrain to the villages in need of help.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be welcomed like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and bloom – with his wide smile and limitless energy – is happy to attend the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team starts examining hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per ride,” says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford it.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, town hall, or apartment; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the rest area to make room for the next person.
The lighting for the surgery and disinfection equipment is powered by the generator of the group and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It’s an exhausting curriculum, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They’re drumming all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then returns to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mixture of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that its work is making a huge difference to the people it helps.
One man explained that the free surgery of a fracture of the ankle that he had received now enabled him to work again.
“It’s changing the future of my family,” he said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who is in her second year at Drexel University in Philadelphia studying medicine and volunteering in the Bwelles group.
He is either always in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley who come from the U.S. and Europe and support bloating, this is a chance to gain hands-on experiences they would never get at home.
“We can be in surgery where we help to clot blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley said.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies.
Once in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes care of accommodation, transportation and directions.
“He’s a hero,” O’Malley said.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries.
For Bwelle, almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to have a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise he made to his father brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to relieve the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
