Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, a sewage channel from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
Those who visit Cologne will not pass the cathedral.
Around 157 meters high, the two towers rise into the sky and make it the second tallest church building in Europe.
However, few visitors who admire the two filigree church towers suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the Cologne Underworld.
Meeting point for his guided tours is the Cologne-Tourism Service Center directly at the Cathedral.
The tour starts quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground garage," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a self-sufficient city, and therefore only what was not too large remained of the remnants of the old city walls.
Therefore, most users of the car park today also rush past the Roman remains and just drop off their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal grid bars in the park deck D2.
You can see about five meters high ruins of hand-sized stones.
"These are the remains of the Roman city walls that were built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze says.
Before returning to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look at a dark, 15-metre-deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old dome, which unfortunately is hardly perceived.
The next stop of the tour is the Praetorium, and here the participants descend back into the depths.
Here we experience the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Pretor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means as much as "city of Roman law and city of the Agrippians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the praetorium is the former governor's palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the hallway of the exhibition leads a tunnel access to the Roman sewage canal, which is preserved here at about 120 meters in length.
"You can quietly walk a bit along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers the guests up.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After collecting the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walkable shaft.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater, which was essential for the ritual washings.
To this day, at the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read through varying levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work is expected to begin shortly.
However, a few years will pass until completion.
