In an unprecedented admission, John Kerry said U.S. espionage was “inappropriately far too far.”
John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, pointed to a softening of the defensive stance of the United States with regard to its surveillance programs, saying that espionage in certain cases “has gone too far inappropriately.”
The foreign minister also admitted that he, along with Barack Obama, assumed responsibility for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities became public.
Due to the leaked information, the US government has entered a diplomatic storm of indignation on the part of its allies.
Speaking at the Open Government conference in London, Kerry said: “Without question, the president and I and others in the government have learned of some things that happened almost via autopilot, simply because of the ability to do so, which dates back to World War II and the difficult years of the Cold War, and of course, to 9/11.”
Subsequently, he was the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, “In some cases, this has gone too far inappropriately.”
The President is determined to create clarity and therefore conducts a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons in this process will not be affected.
Kerry, however, insisted that the NSA was a force for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: “We’re dealing with a new world where people are willing to blow themselves up.”
There is radical extremism in the world, committed to killing people, blowing up and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop it before it happens?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people, because we have learned in advance of such plans.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to dispel concerns over alleged U.S. espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue to work with the U.S. in the anti-terrorism efforts, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Tuesday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he spoke to representatives of the European Parliament and other individuals this week and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti-terror organizations due to frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency.
“It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans remain on board with regard to our joint counter-terrorism efforts,” Murphy, who sits in the Senate for the first time as a Democrat and chairs the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview.
In addition, I am going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, regardless of their anger over the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has captured millions of phone data in Europe have strained relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the intelligence service said this week that the reports were inaccurate and were based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and the United States.
Other revelations cited documents handed down by Snowden that the NSA monitored the phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of the national intelligence, James Clapper, defended espionage among allies as necessary and declared that this was customary on both sides.
In all the turmoil, Murphy said his authority is preparing the congress trip to take place this year, and hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other participating Members will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact itinerary would still be worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relationships, he also said there would be some "serious words".
